I have spent a majority of my 20’s eating shit. (my life is AMAZING in so many ways,  but these are the stories  I wish I could have read about people struggling in business when I was mid shit-eating lol — life isn’t all highlight reels)

20y/o I started a fitness coaching company and had over 200 convos before anyone signed up

21 I working 3 jobs, school full time, but realized I wanted to pursue business so I invested my last $ into a program to learn sales

22 I moved across the country from MT to CA with $50 to my name, no job, nowhere to live, I moved in with a mentor who introduced me to NWM.Had 50 conversations before my first enrollment

23 I slept on a mattress on the floor, ate canned beans, and soley invested into my personal growth- (no dating, eating out) worked 16 hours days+. 

24 My business started booming, became a top earner in my company-s burned out- but continued to work even if it felt like a crawling pace

25 Moved cross country to CO, and struggled heavily with mental health and business declined significantly. Packed up & traveled the world as my ‘quarter-life mini crisis.’ continued to educate and invest in myself. 

26 Broken heart & another move to TX. Committed to my spiritual hygiene. I learned that I had to be my biggest believer

ATE SHIT… daily - I would say to my mentor… “I don’t get it I am doing EVERYTHING I have been taught, I am the hardest working person I know, what am I doing wrong?”

“U aren’t doing anything wrong, you’re in your 20’s & eating shit, thats what your 20’s are for… you are compounding your shit-eating phase - you WILL benefit from the fruits of your labor and when you do— you will WIN BIG.” 

27y/o -Shit started clicking, I focused on raising my frequency EVERYDAY, to learn EVERYDAY, take ownership and responsibility for EVERYTHING I do and do not have,I tell myself EVERYDAY ‘Syd, you’ve got knocked down 7x you can stand up for 8.’

The work I’ve done over the last 7 years has compounded and the fruit of those roots are juicy. I still eat shit in little ways everyday (or i’m not growing) but now the pieces of shit that used to feel huge, feel small. I STOPPED WISHING IT WERE EASIER AND I JUST GOT BETTER.

I arrived at a choice point.

Non-stop.

Are you in a season of yes or a season of no?
Who can agree?

I learned early on in my entrepreneurial journey that the one who fails fast and fails often, wins in the long run. 

When I started in my first company at 22 years old, I heard from people that had the life I wanted telling me “go for no” and “every no is just one step closer to a ‘Yes’.” I reached out to 50 people in my first 3 days, they ALL said no. (Later on I realized most people in sales give up after their first 2 or 3 nos.) 

I certainly could have looked at this and said, “I suck, I quit, everyone said no”. But because the successful people were chanting the tunes above about failing fast and often, I quickly got to reprogram my beliefs around failure. 

What happened during those 50 (what seemed like failures) repetitions. My skills got better. I learned what worked. What didn’t. I learned about myself. I planted seeds that to this day I still reap the harvest of. (Every single one of those people ended up coming back around with a yes… no joke)

I see people all the time face one rejection, one no, one door slammed in their face, and they quit. A no is not a failure, a no is an opportunity.

Shifting your relationship with failure to one of excitement and opportunity to grow and sharpen your saw, will get you further than quitting ever will.

Whether you are trying to land a job, make a sale, get that girl to go on a date with you (lol) I promise you, those who attempt to plant the seeds the most frequently, in spite of the rejections and hard nos, will be rewarded.
 
You will get no’s 
You will get ignored
You will get ghosted

In my career I have had well over 4,000 nos. I have had many less yeses, but those yees have transformed my life into something I used to dream of. 

Keep going, because you can have 99 no’s and ONE YES, can change your entire life.

If you are committed to failing slow, you will learn slow, and you will grow slow. But. If you are willing to fail fast, you will learn fast, and as a result, you will GROW fast.

No story No problem.

We are story making machines.

Every time something happens or we interact with something or someone around us, we want to close the loop on that thought and often times we do this through assuming that we know the entire story.

I know for me I used to let whatever story I wanted to make up about the situation drive me into action or in action usually resulting in jealousy, frustration, drama, resolve, closure

I would tell myself whatever story that I wanted to believe about the other person or the situation to make myself feel better and often times down the road when I found out more information I would realize that that story I had created that became my truth was the furthest thing from it

Our brain wants to know the answers to questions and so we make up stories so that we feel like the thought loop is closed & we “solved” the puzzle.

Now…when something happens or I interact with someone that would normally lead to a negative emotion, I tell myself: NO STORY NO PROBLEM.

Someone doesn’t want to join your business? NO STORY NO PROBLEM.- you have no idea what’s actually going on in their life - their “no” probably has nothing to do with you

A guy doesn’t call you back after your date and you’re telling you’re self you’re not good enough… who knows maybe he thought he wasn’t good enough for you. NO STORY NO PROBLEM.

Someone looks at you weird at the office? Instead of making up a story that actually has something to do with you maybe they just had a fight at home or didn’t get any sleep.. NO STORY NO PROBLEM.

It’s not ignorance - it’s being willing to realize that the stories we tell ourselves matter and when we constantly make up fabricated stories that feed our ego and create restlessness in our nervous system. It’s fear, scarcity and survival. And they usually don’t serve us.

At the end of the day- it’s not love
And if you do make a story - at least make it a serving & loving to both parties

No story no problem = happiness + less drama + peace of mind.

‘Have I been choosing myself first?’ (answer was also no)

I committed to being single UNTIL I became my list.

I went to work on deepening my spiritual practices, releasing old programs that weren’t serving me, eliminating limiting beliefs, learning to actually feel my emotions… building up my relationship with me, myself, and I. "In this book Secrets of the Millionaire Mind, T Harv Eker says that if you wanna make a permanent change in your life, stop focusing on the size of your problem and start focusing on the size of you. 

I think of it like this. Small person, big problems, big person, small problems.

Whatever ‘size’ of person you are can dictate how big or small a problem can feel. Everything is relative. You can make your own rating system for yourself. 

Let's say you're a level 3 person. You haven't done a ton of personal development. You're super reactive to your external environment. Little things throw you off. You let others dictate your emotions, and you have a problem that comes into your life. Maybe it's an unexpected bill. A fight with your spouse. A loss in your business. 

That problem, because you are a level 3 person, may feel pretty substantial. It may feel like a 5 or 6 problem. 

BUT, if you can focus on (instead of shrinking the problem) INCREASING THE SIZE OF YOU. Bettering yourself at a personal level. Reading books, expanding your mind. Growing yourself. Meditating. Starting to uncovering some of those limiting beliefs. You upgrade from a victim consciousness of blaming, complaining, justifying into an empowered state of consciousness. You are growing yourself as a person. 

Let's say you grow and grow and grow yourself as a person day after day. And that same level, 4 or 5 problem comes into your life.

The same bill, the same loss in your business, the same fight with your spouse. Because you've grown yourself to a level 8 person those problems start to feel smaller because you grew the size of yourself.

Grow the size of person you are to shrink your problems"

Clean your sh** up

Every week I like to recap my week, make a list of all of the things I may be putting off, need my attention, that have been ‘kinking my hose’ of that I know will be the work that makes everything else work, and I work through each item in order of importance.

It could be having a difficult conversation, cleaning my house cause the mess is distracting me, maybe it’s saying no to meeting up with someone bc you know it is distracting you from your goals.

This practice has helped me stay focused on the important things, and not get buried in things that need my attention and make all of the work I am doing supercharged bc the energetics are cleaned up.
You can’t have the results without the WORK. Without the hard earned wisdom and sweat equity that comes with our results, we would lose what we got as fast as we got it.

"Everything big starts small.

Saying no to ALL distractions (especially the little ones I try to convince myself aren’t a big deal) 

Saying no to going out/unnecessary meetings and calls

Saying no to late nights

Saying no to holidays (yes you read that right)

Saying no to shopping/spending anything extra other than investing in my business and mindset.

Saying no to low vibes

Saying no to scrolling/tv/media

It comes from removing the little things that don’t serve us.

The ATFSO (ability to figure shit out) is underrated… but available to EVERYONE

Don’t let the fear of being new or not knowing something stop you from taking the first step.

With that being said, what it really comes down to, is how willing are you to apply elbow grease and ATFSI to the thing you say you want.

Relationship SOP:

Alexander & I have done a weekly relationship check-in since we started dating. (We run a business together so we are big on systems in our personal life lol) 

Every week we set aside 30 minutes and follow this flow. 

Hope it can support you and the one you love to strengthen your bond and be more intentional. 

P.S. Ladies, I thought for years I would never find someone that wanted this level of intentionality in their relationship…but let me tell you it was worth waiting til I found one that was… he is out there…

1. Review Intentions for our Relationship: (These are a few examples of ours)

- Building a solid foundation for our relationship
- Learning to optimize our life and business within the relationship 
- Fall more deeply in love every day 

2. Clearing table- what is sitting between you that you haven’t talked about or cleared (get it all out here). (We have had some of our best conversations and personal breakthroughs from this alone.)

3. What worked in our relationship this week

4. Acknowledge each other for the week (“I want to acknowledge for…”)

5. One word to describe the relationship

6. How would you rate the relationship on a scale of 1-5

7. How can we support each other next week/what could you use support in

This has been so supportive for us to really realign each week before it can get insane in the chaos of everyday life.
